
What is Git?
Git is a distributed version control system that helps you:

Track changes in your code. 
Collaborate with others without overwriting work. 
Roll back to previous versions if needed.

✅ 1. Setup & Configuration

git config --global user.name "Your Name"
Sets your name for commits globally. 

git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"
Sets your email for commits globally. 

git config --list
Shows all current Git configurations.
✅ 2. Starting a Repository

git init
Initialize a new Git repository in the current folder. 

git clone <repo-url>
Clone an existing remote repository to your local machine.
✅ 3. Checking Status

git status
Shows which files are modified, staged, or untracked. 


 ✅ 4. Adding Files

git add <file>
Stage a specific file for commit. 

git add .
Stage all changes in the current directory. 


 ✅ 5. Committing Changes

git commit -m "Commit message"
Commit staged changes with a message. 

git commit -am "Commit message"
Add and commit tracked files in one step. 


 ✅ 6. Branching

git branch
List all branches. 

git branch <branch-name>
Create a new branch. 

git checkout <branch-name>
Switch to a branch. 

git switch <branch-name> (modern alternative to checkout) 
git merge <branch-name>
Merge another branch into the current branch. 


 ✅ 7. Remote Operations

git remote -v
View remote repositories. 

git push origin <branch>
Push local commits to remote branch. 

git pull origin <branch>
Fetch and merge changes from remote branch. 

git fetch
Download changes from remote without merging. 


 ✅ 8. Viewing History

git log
View commit history. 

git log --oneline --graph --decorate
Compact history with branch visualization. 


 ✅ 9. Comparing Changes

git diff
Show changes not staged. 

git diff --staged
Show staged changes ready for commit. 


 ✅ 10. Undoing Changes

git reset <file>
Unstage a file. 

git checkout -- <file>
Discard changes in a file. 

git revert <commit>
Undo a commit by creating a new one. 


 ✅ 11. Stashing

git stash
Save changes temporarily without committing. 

git stash pop
Apply stashed changes back. 


 ✅ 12. Tags

git tag <tag-name>
Create a tag for a specific commit. 

git push origin --tags
Push tags remotely.

✅ 13. Aliases for Efficiency
git config --global alias.st status
git config --global alias.co checkout
git config --global alias.br branch
